cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.CC, cs.GT. 

The problem deals with geometric objects (points, lines, and partitions of the plane), which suggests that it belongs to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of fixed-parameter algorithms also suggests that it could belong to the parameterized complexity (cs.DS) sub-category. The discretization aspect of the problem suggests that it could belong to the data structures and algorithms (cs.DM) sub-category. The use of optimization and the study of the minimum size of a family of lines suggests that it could belong to the computational complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. Finally, the study of the separation of two disjoint sets of points suggests that it could belong to the game theory and economics (cs.GT) sub-category.
